erous child into a raider, mercenary, litigant, landholder, and poet epitomizes the many facets of Viking legend.The contributors to this collection of essays approach Egil’s story from a variety of perspectives, including psychology, philology, network theory, social history, and literary theory. Strikingly original, their essays will appeal not only to dedicated students of Old Norse-Icelandic literature but also to those working in the fields of Viking studies, comparative ethnology, and folklore.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSagasxHistory and criticismxCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aSagasxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAppleton, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Looze, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Oren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinlay, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelgason, Jon Karl, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHelgason, Jón Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJakobsson, Ármann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordal, Guđrún, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParsons, Katelin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoole, Russell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoole, Russell, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoss, Margaret Clunies, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTangherlini, Timothy R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTulinius, Torfi H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov